18 Jun 2004 <http://www.oie.int/eng/info/hebdo/AIS_40.HTM#Sec6>
Translation of information received on 21 Oct 2005 from Dr. Jorge
Caetano Junior, Director, Department of Animal Protection (DDA),
Ministry of Agriculture, Livestock and Food Supply, Brasilia:
End of previous report period: 17 Oct 2005 (see Disease Information,
18 [42], 358, dated 21 Oct 2005).
End of this report period: 20 Oct 2005.
Precise identification of agent: foot and mouth disease (FMD) virus serotype O.
Date of 1st confirmation of the event: 8 Oct 2005.
Date of start of the event: 26 Sep 2005.
Nature of diagnosis: clinical and laboratory.
Details of new outbreaks:
1st administrative division (State) / Lower administrative division
(municipality) / Type of epidemiological unit / Date of start of the
outbreak / Species / Number of animals in the outbreaks
susceptible / cases / deaths / destroyed / slaughtered
Mato Grosso do Sul / Japora / farm / 13 Oct 2005 / bov
253 / 16 / 0 / 0 / 0
Mato Grosso do Sul / Japora / farm / 12 Oct 2005
bov / 52 / 12 / 0 / 0 / 0
Mato Grosso do Sul / Japora / farm / 17 Oct 2005
bov / 16 / 2 / 0 / 0 / 0
Mato Grosso do Sul / Japora / farm / 17 Oct 2005
bov / 142 / 20 / 0 / 0 / 0
Mato Grosso do Sul / Mundo Novo / farm / 16 Oct 2005
bov / 777 / 5 / 0 / 0 / 0
Description of affected population: fattening cattle reared on
pasture. There have been no reports of suspected cases in species
other than bovines.
In Japora district, surveillance activities led to the detection of 4
new outbreaks, on the basis of a clinico-epidemiological diagnosis:
- The 1st farm has 253 cattle, 16 of which (one animal aged less than
4 months, 9 animals aged between 12 and 24 months and 6 animals aged
over 24 months) were sick.
- The 2nd farm has 52 animals, 12 of which (7 aged between 12 and 24
months, 5 aged between 24 and 26 months) showed clinical signs of
foot and mouth disease.
- The 3rd farm has 16 cattle (2 sick: one animal aged less than 4
months and one animal aged over 24 months).
- The 4th farm has 142 cattle, 20 of which (all aged between 12 and
24 months) presented clinical signs.
In Mundo Novo district, an outbreak was detected on the basis of a
clinico-epidemiological diagnosis in a large herd of beef cattle
totaling 777 animals. 5 of these animals (aged over 24 months)
presented clinical signs. The affected farm is very close to Japora district.
Source of outbreaks: unknown or inconclusive (investigations in progress).
Control measures:
- Stamping out (in progress). Weather conditions (heavy rain) are
hampering the culling and destruction of animals in the outbreaks.
- Disinfection of infected premises.
- To date, 924 farms with a total population of 122 578 cattle, 3230
sheep and goats and 2713 pigs have been inspected in the zone where a
movement ban is in force.
- The municipalities of Eldorado, Iguatemi, Itaquirai, Japora and
Mundo Novo remain under quarantine. 12 checkpoints were set up to
prevent any movement of FMD-susceptible animals or their
products/by-products originating from these districts to national or
international markets.
- The 25-km-radius safety zone around the new outbreaks lies
completely within the boundary of the aforementioned 5 districts.
The control measures in the region involve the use of material and
human resources from the State and Federal governments with
assistance from the public forces at fixed checkpoints and mobile teams.
Final report: no.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[This virus appears to be the same one that has circulated in the
several South American countries beginning in 2000. Also, no pigs
have tested positive. The source of these outbreaks is unknown at
present, but the serious nature of the apparent spread from Mato
Grosso do Sul to Parana is undeniable. Hopefully, attempts to
regionalize this outbreak and then clean it up will meet with
success. - Mod.PC]
